<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-468-684  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 468 684.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>InfoWorld  July 31 1989 v11 n31 p34(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Adapso pushes virus legislation; report recommends specifyingunlawful acts and federal penalties. (Association of DataProcessing Service Organizations)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Mace, Scott.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Association of Data Processing Service Organizations (ADAPSO)is recommending amendments to the 1986 Computer Fraud and AbuseAct that would cover computer viruses.andP;  ADAPSO's recommendationswould: specify federal penalties for 'computer program tampering'and for the disruption of computer systems, define access, outlawaccess that exceeds authorization and which results in damage, andexpand the definition of 'computer' to cover laptop machines.andO;Federal officials say they may be unable to successfully prosecutecreators of computer viruses without changes in the law.andP;  TheHouse Subcommittee on Telecommunications and Finance is draftinglegislation that may incorporate ADAPSO's suggestions, and theGeneral Accounting Office has recommended that President Bush'sscience adviser establish an interagency group to provide securityon the Internet.andP;  Internet was seriously disrupted by a computervirus Nov 1988.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Statute:   Computer Fraud and Abuse Act of 1986 (amendments).andO;Topic:     Association of Data Processing Service OrganizationsLegal IssuesComputer VirusesData SecurityComputer CrimesGovernment Regulation.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>